Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: While the original "Deliberative Norm Learning" (DNL) idea makes a strong conceptual leap by grounding AI alignment in democratic deliberation, it risks treating deliberation as a static training signal rather than an ongoing, adaptive process embedded within sociotechnical systems. Drawing inspiration from Paper 1’s critique of superficial democratization, I recognize that true democratic integration requires more than simulating deliberation—it demands structural inclusion of marginalized voices and institutional accountability. Paper 2’s differentiable symbolic reasoning offers a technical pathway for interpretability, but its logic is abstracted from social context. Meanwhile, Paper 3 introduces efficient, parallel deliberative correction in SLU, suggesting that iterative refinement can be both fast and robust. My new idea advances DNL by shifting from *simulated internal learning* to *participatory external co-governance*: instead of merely modeling deliberation, AI systems should be designed to **continuously incorporate real-time, pluralistic public input through lightweight, scalable democratic interfaces**. This leads to “Democratic Alignment Loops” (DAL), where NLP models are not just trained on past deliberations but remain open to normative updates via structured civic feedback mechanisms—akin to a constitutional amendment process for AI behavior. The key innovation lies in creating bidirectional accountability: models generate policy-relevant outputs, which are then exposed to inclusive, moderated digital forums where participants deliberate and vote on normative corrections. These collective judgments are encoded into symbolic rules via a differentiable logic module (inspired by DSR-LM), which updates model constraints without full retraining. Unlike RLHF—which reflects individual preferences—or constitutional AI—which encodes top-down principles—DAL operationalizes *collective justification* under conditions of equality and reciprocity. This approach also introduces procedural legitimacy: users can see how and why a model changed, based on transparent, auditable civic inputs. It transforms AI alignment from a one-off engineering task into a sustained democratic practice.

